data.content:
Your test works but `Assert.IsTrue` gives unhelpful failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). Use specialized collection assertions instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Before | After | Why |
|--------|-------|-----|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "Expected count: 3, Actual: 2" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Clearer intent + better message |

For the admin check specifically, if you want to assert exactly one admin exists:

```csharp
var admins = users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin").ToList();
var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(admins);
Assert.AreEqual("Admin", admin.Role); // further assertions on the element
```

`Assert.ContainsSingle` both verifies the collection has exactly one element **and** returns it for further inspection.
